"[{\"id\":2801551,\"solution\":\"[p]第一步，找定位词：比较级定位 much harder，比较定位 increased inequality[/p][p]第二步，段落定位：&#91;H&#93; Some San Jose residents say that as [u]inequality has grown[/u] in recent years, upward mobility has become [u]much more difficult[/u] to achieve.[/p][p]第三步，寻找同义替换[/p][p]题干/原文[/p][p]much harder/ much more difficult[/p][p]increased / grown[/p][p]people living in.../ residents[/p]\",\"source\":\"2020年12月大学英语四级考试题（一）第36题\",\"tags\":[],\"flags\":[],\"solutionAccessories\":[]},{\"id\":2801559,\"solution\":\"[p]第一步，找定位词：词组定位American history、a good chance，名词定位 immigrants[/p][p]第二步，段落定位：&#91;D&#93; This is a city of [u]immigrants[/u]--38 percent of the city's population today is foreign-born--and [u]immigrants[/u] and their children have [u]historically[/u] experienced [u]significant[/u] upward mobility in [u]America[/u].[/p][p]第三步，寻找同义替换[/p][p]题干/原文[/p][p]history / historically[/p][p]move upward / upward mobility[/p][p]good / significant[/p]\",\"source\":\"2020年12月大学英语四级考试题（一）第37题\",\"tags\":[],\"flags\":[],\"solutionAccessories\":[]},{\"id\":2801665,\"solution\":\"[p]第一步，找定位词：否定定位 can’t be solved，词组定位 fundamental beliefs[/p][p]第二步，段落定位：&#91;K&#93; That such mobility has become more difficult in San Jose raises questions about the endurance of that [u]foundational belief[/u]. After all, if the one-time land of opportunity [u]can't be fixed[/u], what does that say for the rest of America?第三步，寻找同义替换[/p][p]题干/原文[/p][p]solved / fixed[/p][p]fundamental / foundational[/p]\",\"source\":\"2020年12月大学英语四级考试题（一）第38题\",\"tags\":[],\"flags\":[],\"solutionAccessories\":[]},{\"id\":2801675,\"solution\":\"[p]第一步，找定位词：最高级定位 best cities，词组定位 social ladder[/p][p]第二步，段落定位：&#91;B&#93; Indeed, data suggests that this is one of the [u]best places[/u] to grow up poor in America. ...That number—12.9 percent—may not seem remarkable, but it was: Kids in San Jose whose families fell in the [u]bottom[/u] quintile(五分位数)of income nationally had the best shot in the country at reaching the [u]top[/u] quintile.[/p][p]第三步，寻找同义替换[/p][p]题干/原文[/p][p]best cities / best places[/p][p]social ladder / bottom...top[/p]\",\"source\":\"2020年12月大学英语四级考试题（一）第39题\",\"tags\":[],\"flags\":[],\"solutionAccessories\":[]},{\"id\":2801680,\"solution\":\"[p]第一步，找定位词：词组定位 whether... have the chance，时间定位 today[/p][p]第二步，段落定位：&#91;G&#93; [u]Whether[/u] the city still [u]allows for[/u] upward mobility of poor kids[u] today[/u], though, is up for debate.[/p][p]第三步，寻找同义替换[/p][p]题干/原文[/p][p]have the chance / allows for[/p][p]move upward / upward mobility[/p][p]questionable / up for debate[/p]\",\"source\":\"2020年12月大学英语四级考试题（一）第40题\",\"tags\":[],\"flags\":[],\"solutionAccessories\":[]},{\"id\":2801689,\"solution\":\"[p]第一步，找定位词：名词定位 officials，词组定位 access to the resources[/p][p]第二步，段落定位：&#91;I&#93; [u]Leaders[/u] in SanJose are determined to make sure that the city regains its status as a place where even poor kids can [u]access the resources[/u] to succeed.[/p][p]第三步，寻找同义替换[/p][p]题干/原文[/p][p]officials / leaders[/p][p]are resolved to / are determined to[/p][p]success / succeed[/p]\",\"source\":\"2020年12月大学英语四级考试题（一）第41题\",\"tags\":[],\"flags\":[],\"solutionAccessories\":[]},{\"id\":2801713,\"solution\":\"[p]第一步，找定位词：最高级定位 best features of America[/p][p]第二步，段落定位：&#91;E&#93; Indeed, the streets of SanJose seem, in some ways, to embody the [u]best of America[/u].[/p][p]第三步，寻找同义替换[/p][p]题干/原文[/p][p]appears       "body": "[{\"id\":2801551,\"content\":\"[p]According to some people living in San Jose, it has become much harder for the poor to get ahead due to the increased inequality. [/p]\",\"material\":{\"id\":272640,\"content\":\"[p=align:center][b]The Place Where the Poor Once Thrived[/b][trans][b]一个穷人曾经欣欣向荣的地方[/b][/trans][/p][p] [b]&#91;A&#93;[/b] This is the land of opportunity. If that weren’t already implied by the landscape—rolling green hills, palm trees, sun-kissed flowers—then it’s evident in the many stories of people who [phrase=171239]grew up[/phrase] poor in these sleepy neighborhoods and rose to enormous success. People like Tri Tran, who fled Vietnam on a boat in 1986, showed up in San Jose with nothing, made it to MIT, and then founded the food-delivery start-up Munchery, which is valued at $300 million. [trans][b]      &#91; A&#93;[/b]这是一片充满机遇的十地，即这里的风景——连绵起伏的青山、棕榈树、阳光亲吻的花朵——没有暗示出这样的机遇，那么从许多在这些寂静的社区里成长，并获得了巨大成功的穷人的故事中就可以明显地看出这一点。特里·特兰等人于1986年乘船逃离越南，到达圣何塞时一无所有，然后成功地进入麻省理工学院，之后创立了送餐初创公司Munchery（吃不厌的外卖订餐网站），目前估值3亿美元。[/trans][/p][p] [b]&#91;B&#93;[/b] Indeed, data suggests that this is one of the best places to [phrase=171239]grow up[/phrase] poor in America. A child born in the early 1980s into a low-income family in San Jose had a 12.9 percent chance of becoming a high earner as an adult, [phrase=158128]according to[/phrase] a landmark study released in 2014 by the economist Raj Chetty and his colleagues from Harvard and Berkeley. That number—12.9 percent—may not seem remarkable, but it was: Kids in San Jose whose families fell in the bottom [i]quintile[/i] (五分位数) of income nationally had the best shot in the country at reaching the top quintile. [trans][b]      [/b][b]&#91;B&#93;[/b]（39）[u]事实上，数据显示这是美国最适合穷人成长的地方之一。2014年，哈佛大学及伯克利分校的经济学家拉吉·切蒂及其同事发布了一项具有里程碑意义的研究。根据这项研究，20世纪80年代初出生于圣何塞低收入家庭的孩子成年后成为高收入者的概率为12.9%，这一数字——12.9%——似乎并不令人瞩目，但它确实令人瞩目：圣何塞那些收入在全国最低的五分之一的家庭的孩子，最有可能成为全国收入最高的五分之一。[/u][/trans][/p][p] [b]&#91;C&#93;[/b] [phrase=197882]By contrast[/phrase], just 4.4 percent of poor kids in Charlotte [phrase=177699]moved up[/phrase] to the top; in Detroit the figure was 5.5 percent. San Jose had social mobility comparable to Denmark’s and Canada’s and higher than other progressive cities [phrase=201452]such as[/phrase] Boston and Minneapolis.[trans][b]      [/b][b]&#91;C&#93;[/b]相比之下，夏洛特市只有4.4%的贫困儿童升入顶端；底特律的这一比例为5.5%。（43）[u]圣何塞的社会流动性可与丹麦和加拿大相提并论，高于波士顿和明尼阿波利斯等其他进步城市。[/u][/trans][/p][p] [b]&#91;D&#93;[/b] The reasons kids in San Jose performed so well might seem obvious. Some of the world’s most innovative companies are located here, providing opportunities [phrase=201452]such as[/phrase] the one seized by a 12-year-old Mountain View resident named Steve Jobs when he called William Hewlett to ask for spare parts and subsequently received a summer job. This is a city of immigrants—38 percent of the city’s population today is foreign-born—and immigrants and their children have historically experienced significant upward mobility in America. The city has long had a large foreign-born population (26.5 percent in 1990), leading to broader diversity, which, the Harvard and Berkeley economists say, is a good predictor of mobility. [trans][b]      [/b][b]&#91;D&#93;[/b]圣何塞的孩子表现如此出色的原因似乎是显而易见的。一些世界上最具创新精神的公司都坐落在这里，提供了这样的机会，比如：12岁的山景城居民史蒂夫·乔布斯就抓住了这样的机会。当时，他给威廉·休利特打电话申请备用件，随后获得了一份暑期工作。（37）[u]这是一个移民城市——如今该市38%的人口是在外国出生的——在美国历史上，移民及其子女经历了社会中显著的向上流动。[/u]长期以来，这座城市拥有大量的外国出生人口（1990年为26.5%），这导致了更广泛的多样性，哈佛大学和伯克利分校的经济学家说，这是一个很好的预测流动性的指标。[/trans][/p][p] [b]&#91;E&#93;[/b] Indeed, the streets of San Jose seem, [phrase=201349]in some ways[/phrase], to embody the best of America. It’s possible to drive in [phrase=201487]a matter of[/phrase] minutes from [i]sleek[/i] (光亮的) office towers near the airport where people pitch ideas to investors, to single-family homes with orange trees in their yards, or to a Vietnamese mall. The libraries here offer programs in 17 languages, and there are areas [phrase=201213]filled with[/phrase] small businesses owned by Vietnamese immigrants, Mexican immigrants, Korean immigrants, and Filipino immigrants, to name [phrase=201394]a few[/phrase]. [trans][b]      [/b][b]&#91;E&#93;[/b]（42）[u]的确，在某些方面，圣何塞的街道似乎体现了美国最好的一面。[/u]人们可以在机场附近时尚光亮的写字楼里向投资者推销创意，也可以在几分钟内驱车前往院子里种着橘子树的独户住宅，或者到一个越南购物中心。这里的图书馆提供17种语言的项目，并且这里到处都是由越南移民、墨西哥移民、韩国移民、菲律宾移民（举几个例子）经营的小企业。[/trans][/p][p] [b]&#91;F&#93;[/b] But researchers aren’t sure exactly why poor kids in San Jose did so well. If that weren’t already implied by the landscape—rolling green hills, palm trees, sun-kissed flowers—then it’s evident in the many stories of people who [phrase=171239]grew up[/phrase] poor in these sleepy neighborhoods and rose to enormous success. People like Tri Tran, who fled Vietnam on a boat in 1986, showed up in San Jose with nothing, made it to MIT, and then founded the food-delivery start-up Munchery, which is valued at $300 million. [trans][b]      &#91; A&#93;[/b]这是一片充满机遇的十地，即这里的风景——连绵起伏的青山、棕榈树、阳光亲吻的花朵——没有暗示出这样的机遇，那么从许多在这些寂静的社区里成长，并获得了巨大成功的穷人的故事中就可以明显地看出这一点。特里·特兰等人于1986年乘船逃离越南，到达圣何塞时一无所有，然后成功地进入麻省理工学院，之后创立了送餐初创公司Munchery（吃不厌的外卖订餐网站），目前估值3亿美元。[/trans][/p][p] [b]&#91;B&#93;[/b] Indeed, data suggests that this is one of the best places to [phrase=171239]grow up[/phrase] poor in America. That number—12.9 percent—may not seem remarkable, but it was: Kids in San Jose whose families fell in the bottom [i]quintile[/i] (五分位数) of income nationally had the best shot in the country at reaching the top quintile. [trans][b]      [/b][b]&#91;B&#93;[/b]（39）[u]事实上，数据显示这是美国最适合穷人成长的地方之一。2014年，哈佛大学及伯克利分校的经济学家拉吉·切蒂及其同事发布了一项具有里程碑意义的研究。根据这项研究，20世纪80年代初出生于圣何塞低收入家庭的孩子成年后成为高收入者的概率为12.9%，这一数字——12.9%——似乎并不令人瞩目，但它确实令人瞩目：圣何塞那些收入在全国最低的五分之一的家庭的孩子，最有可能成为全国收入最高的五分之一。[/u][/trans][/p][p] [b]&#91;C&#93;[/b] [phrase=197882]By contrast[/phrase], just 4.4 percent of poor kids in Charlotte [phrase=177699]moved up[/phrase] to the top; in Detroit the figure was 5.5 percent. San Jose had social mobility comparable to Denmark’s and Canada’s and higher than other progressive cities [phrase=201452]such as[/phrase] Boston and Minneapolis.[trans][b]      [/b][b]&#91;C&#93;[/b]相比之下，夏洛特市只有4.4%的贫困儿童升入顶端；底特律的这一比例为5.5%。（43）[u]圣何塞的社会流动性可与丹麦和加拿大相提并论，高于波士顿和明尼阿波利斯等其他进步城市。[/u][/trans][/p][p] [b]&#91;D&#93;[/b] The reasons kids in San Jose performed so well might seem obvious. Some of the world’s most innovative companies are located here, providing opportunities [phrase=201452]such as[/phrase] the one seized by a 12-year-old Mountain View resident named Steve Jobs when he called William Hewlett to ask for spare parts and subsequently received a summer job. This is a city of immigrants—38 percent of the city’s population today is foreign-born—and immigrants and their children have historically experienced significant upward mobility in America. If that weren’t already implied by the landscape—rolling green hills, palm trees, sun-kissed flowers—then it’s evident in the many stories of people who [phrase=171239]grew up[/phrase] poor in these sleepy neighborhoods and rose to enormous success. People like Tri Tran, who fled Vietnam on a boat in 1986, showed up in San Jose with nothing, made it to MIT, and then founded the food-delivery start-up Munchery, which is valued at $300 million. [trans][b]      &#91; A&#93;[/b]这是一片充满机遇的十地，即这里的风景——连绵起伏的青山、棕榈树、阳光亲吻的花朵——没有暗示出这样的机遇，那么从许多在这些寂静的社区里成长，并获得了巨大成功的穷人的故事中就可以明显地看出这一点。特里·特兰等人于1986年乘船逃离越南，到达圣何塞时一无所有，然后成功地进入麻省理工学院，之后创立了送餐初创公司Munchery（吃不厌的外卖订餐网站），目前估值3亿美元。[/trans][/p][p] [b]&#91;B&#93;[/b] Indeed, data suggests that this is one of the best places to [phrase=171239]grow up[/phrase] poor in America. A child born in the early 1980s into a low-income family in San Jose had a 12.9 percent chance of becoming a high earner as an adult, [phrase=158128]according to[/phrase] a landmark study released in 2014 by the economist Raj Chetty and his colleagues from Harvard and Berkeley. That number—12.9 percent—may not seem remarkable, but it was: Kids in San Jose whose families fell in the bottom [i]quintile[/i] (五分位数) of income nationally had the best shot in the country at reaching the top quintile.   [/b][b]&#91;K&#93;[/b]（38）[u]认为底层的人可以上升到上层的想法是美国自我观念的核心。这种流动性在圣何塞变得越来越困难，引发了人们对该基本信念的持久性质疑。毕竟，如果无法修复这片曾经的机会之地，那对美国其他地区来说又意味着什么呢？[/u][/p]\",\"words\":null,\"transWords\":null,\"title\":\"2020年12月 poor kids in San Jose today still have the chance to move upward is questionable. [/p]\",\"material\":{\"id\":272640,\"content\":\"[p=align:center][b]The Place Where the Poor Once Thrived[/b][trans][b]一个穷人曾经欣欣向荣的地方[/b][/trans][/p][p] [b]&#91;A&#93;[/b] This is the land of opportunity. If that weren’t already implied by the landscape—rolling green hills, palm trees, sun-kissed flowers—then it’s evident in the many stories of people who [phrase=171239]grew up[/phrase] poor in these sleepy neighborhoods and rose to enormous success. People like Tri Tran, who fled Vietnam on a boat in 1986, showed up in San Jose with nothing, made it to MIT, and then founded the food-delivery start-up Munchery, which is valued at $300 million. [trans][b]      &#91; A&#93;[/b]这是一片充满机遇的十地，即这里的风景——连绵起伏的青山、棕榈树、阳光亲吻的花朵——没有暗示出这样的机遇，那么从许多在这些寂静的社区里成长，并获得了巨大成功的穷人的故事中就可以明显地看出这一点。特里·特兰等人于1986年乘船逃离越南，到达圣何塞时一无所有，然后成功地进入麻省理工学院，之后创立了送餐初创公司Munchery（吃不厌的外卖订餐网站），目前估值3亿美元。[/trans][/p][p] [b]&#91;B&#93;[/b] Indeed, data suggests that this is one of the best places to [phrase=171239]grow up[/phrase] poor in America. A child born in the early 1980s into a low-income family in San Jose had a 12.9 percent chance of becoming a high earner as an adult, [phrase=158128]according to[/phrase] a landmark study released in 2014 by the economist Raj Chetty and his colleagues from Harvard and Berkeley. That number—12.9 percent—may not seem remarkable, but it was: Kids in San Jose whose families fell in the bottom [i]quintile[/i] (五分位数) of income nationally had the best shot in the country at reaching the top quintile. [trans][b]      [/b][b]&#91;B&#93;[/b]（39）[u]事实上，数据显示这是美国最适合穷人成长的地方之一。2014年，哈佛大学及伯克利分校的经济学家拉吉·切蒂及其同事发布了一项具有里程碑意义的研究。根据这项研究，20世纪80年代初出生于圣何塞低收入家庭的孩子成年后成为高收入者的概率为12.9%，这一数字——12.9%——似乎并不令人瞩目，但它确实令人瞩目：圣何塞那些收入在全国最低的五分之一的家庭的孩子，最有可能成为全国收入最高的五分之一。[/u][/trans][/p][p] [b]&#91;C&#93;[/b] [phrase=197882]By contrast[/phrase], just 4.4 percent of poor kids in Charlotte [phrase=177699]moved up[/phrase] to the top; in Detroit the figure was 5.5 percent. San Jose had social mobility comparable to Denmark’s and Canada’s and higher than other progressive cities [phrase=201452]such as[/phrase] Boston and Minneapolis.[trans][b]      [/b][b]&#91;C&#93;[/b]相比之下，夏洛特市只有4.4%的贫困儿童升入顶端；底特律的这一比例为5.5%。（43）[u]圣何塞的社会流动性可与丹麦和加拿大相提并论，高于波士顿和明尼阿波利斯等其他进步城市。[/u][/trans][/p][p] [b]&#91;D&#93;[/b] The reasons kids in San Jose performed so well might seem obvious. Some of the world’s most innovative companies are located here, providing opportunities [phrase=201452]such as[/phrase] the one seized by a 12-year-old Mountain View resident named Steve Jobs when he called William Hewlett to ask for spare parts and subsequently received a summer job. This is a city of immigrants—38 percent of the city’s population today is foreign-born—and immigrants and their children have historically experienced significant upward mobility in America. The city has long had a large foreign-born population (26.5 percent in 1990), leading to broader diversity, which, the Harvard and Berkeley economists say, is a good predictor of mobility. [trans][b]      [/b][b]&#91;D&#93;[/b]圣何塞的孩子表现如此出色的原因似乎是显而易见的。一些世界上最具创新精神的公司都坐落在这里，提供了这样的机会，比如：12岁的山景城居民史蒂夫·乔布斯就抓住了这样的机会。当时，他给威廉·休利特打电话申请备用件，随后获得了一份暑期工作。（37）[u]这是一个移民城市——如今该市38%的人口是在外国出生的——在美国历史上，移民及其子女经历了社会中显著的向上流动。[/u]长期以来，这座城市拥有大量的外国出生人口（1990年为26.5%），这导致了更广泛的多样性，哈佛大学和伯克利分校的经济学家说，这是一个很好的预测流动性的指标。[/trans][/p][p] [b]&#91;E&#93;[/b] Indeed, the streets of San Jose seem, [phrase=201349]in some ways[/phrase], to embody the best of America. It’s possible to drive in [phrase=201487]a matter of[/phrase] minutes from [i]sleek[/i] (光亮的) office towers near the airport where people pitch ideas to investors, to single-family homes with orange trees in their yards, or to a Vietnamese mall. The libraries here offer programs in 17 languages, and there are areas [phrase=201213]filled with[/phrase] small businesses owned by Vietnamese immigrants, Mexican immigrants, Korean immigrants, and Filipino immigrants, to name [phrase=201394]a few[/phrase]. [trans][b]      [/b][b]&#91;E&#93;[/b]（42）[u]的确，在某些方面，圣何塞的街道似乎体现了美国最好的一面。[/u]人们可以在机场附近时尚光亮的写字楼里向投资者推销创意，也可以在几分钟内驱车前往院子里种着橘子树的独户住宅，或者到一个越南购物中心。这里的图书馆提供17种语言的项目，并且这里到处都是由越南移民、墨西哥移民、韩国移民、菲律宾移民（举几个例子）经营的小企业。[/trans][/p][p] [b]&#91;F&#93;[/b] But researchers aren’t sure exactly why poor kids in San Jose did so well. The city has a low prevalence of children [phrase=171239]growing up[/phrase] in single-parent families, and a low level of concentrated poverty, both factors that usually mean a city [phrase=158691]allows for[/phrase] good intergenerational mobility. But San Jose also performs poorly on some of the measures [phrase=201477]correlated with[/phrase] good mobility. It is one of the most unequal places out of the 741 that the researchers measured, and it has high degrees of racial and economic [i]segregation[/i] (隔离). Its schools underperform based on how much money there is in the area, said Ben Scuderi, a predoctoral fellow at the Equality of Opportunity Project at Harvard, which uses big data to study how to improve economic opportunities for low-income children. “There’s [phrase=112277]a lot[/phrase] [phrase=170649]going on[/phrase] here which we don’t totally understand,” he said. “It’s interesting, because it [phrase=174474]kind of[/phrase] defies our expectations.”[trans][b]      [/b][b]&#91;F&#93;[/b]（43）[u]但研究人员并不能完全确定为什么圣何塞的穷孩子做得这么好。[/u]这座城市的单亲家庭儿童比例较低，集中贫困程度较低，这两个因素通常意味着一个城市能够实现良好的代际流动。但圣何塞在一些与良好流动性相关的指标方面也表现不佳。在研究人员测量的741个地方中，它是最不平等的地方之一，它有着高度的种族和经济隔离。哈佛大学机会均等项目利用大数据研究如何改善低收入儿童的经济机会。该项目博士预科研究员本·斯库德利表示，根据该地区的资金状况，这里的学校表现不佳。他说：“这里有很多我们不能完全理解的事情。这很有趣，因为这有点儿出乎我们的意料。”[/trans][/p][p] [b]&#91;G&#93;[/b] The Chetty data shows that neighborhoods and places mattered for children born in the San Jose area of the 1980s. Whether the city still [phrase=158691]allows for[/phrase] upward mobility of poor kids today, though, is up for debate. Some of the indicators [phrase=201452]such as[/phrase] income inequality, measured by the Equality of Opportunity Project for the year 2000, have only worsened in the past 16 years.[trans][b]      [/b][b]&#91;G&#93;[/b]切蒂的数据显示，对于20世纪80年代出生在圣何塞地区的孩子来说，社区和地方至关重要。（40）[u]不过，如今这座城市是否还允许贫困儿童向上流动，还有待商榷。[/u]一些指标，如2000年机会平等项目衡量的收入不平等，在过去16年里恶化了。[/trans][/p][p] [b]&#91;H&#93;[/b] Some San Jose residents say that as inequality has grown in recent years, upward mobility has become much more difficult to achieve. As Silicon Valley has become home to more successful companies, the flood of people to the area has caused housing prices to skyrocket. By most measures, San Jose is [phrase=178433]no longer[/phrase] a place where low-income, or even middle-income families, can [phrase=196421]afford to[/phrase] live. Rents in San Jose grew 42.6 percent between 2006 and 2014, which was the largest increase in the country during that time period. The city has a growing homelessness problem, which it tried to address by [phrase=185688]shutting down[/phrase] “The Jungle,” one of the largest homeless [i]encampments[/i] (临时住地) in the nation, in 2014. Inequality is extreme. The Human Development Index—a measure of life expectancy, education and [i]per capita[/i] (人均的) income—gives East San Jose a score of 4.85 out of 10, while nearby Cupertino, where Apple’s headquarters sits, receives a 9.26, San Jose [phrase=148491]used to[/phrase] have a happy mix of factors—cheap housing, closeness to a rapidly developing industry, tightly-knit immigrant communities—that together [phrase=179401]opened up[/phrase] the possibility of prosperity for even its poorest residents. But in recent years, housing prices have skyrocketed, the region’s rich and poor have segregated, and middle-class jobs have disappeared. Given this, the future for the region’s poor doesn’t look nearly as bright as it once did. [trans][b]      [/b][b]&#91;H&#93;[/b]（36）[u]一些圣何塞居民说，随着近年来不平等的加剧，向上流动变得更加困难。[/u]随着硅谷成为更多成功企业的发源地，大量人口涌入该地区，导致房价飙升。从大多数标准来看，圣何塞已不再是低收入甚至中等收入家庭能够负担得起生活的地方。2006年至2014年期间，圣何塞的房租上涨了42.6%，是该国同期租金涨幅最大的。这座城市无家可归的问题日益严重，人们在2014年试图通过关闭美国最大的无家可归者临时居住地之一“丛林”来解决这个问题。不平等现象极为严重。人类发展指数——衡量预期寿命、受教育程度和人均收入的指标——为东圣何塞打出4.85分（满分为10分），而附近的苹果总部所在地库比蒂诺得分为9.26分。圣何塞过去曾经拥有许多令人愉快的因素——廉价的住房、靠近快速发展的工业、紧密联系的移民社区——这些共同为即使是最贫困的居民带来了繁荣的可能性。（44）[u]但近年来，房价飞涨，该地区贫富分化，中产阶级工作岗位消失。鉴于此，该地区穷人的未来看起来不像以前那么光明了。[/u][/trans][/p][p] [b]&#91;I&#93;[/b] Leaders in San Jose are determined to [phrase=176325]make sure[/phrase] that the city regains its status as a place where even poor kids can access the resources to succeed. With Silicon Valley in its backyard, it certainly has the chance to do so. “I think there is a broad consciousness in the Valley that we can do better than to leave thousands of our neighbors behind through a period of extraordinary success,” San Jose Mayor Sam Liccardo said.[trans][b]      [/b][b]&#91;I&#93;（[/b]41）[u]圣何塞的领导人决心确保该市重新获得它的地位，再次成为一个即使是贫穷的孩子也可以获取成功资源的地方。[/u]硅谷就在它的后院，它当然有机会做到这一点。圣何塞市长萨姆·利卡多说：“我认为，硅谷有一个广泛的意识，我们可以做得更好，而不是让成千上万的邻居在一个非凡的成功时期被抛在身后。”[/trans][/p][p] [b]&#91;J&#93;[/b] But in today’s America—a land of rising inequality, increasing segregation, and [i]stagnating[/i] (不增长的) middle-class wages—can the San Jose region really [phrase=179282]once again[/phrase] become a place of opportunity? [trans][b]      [/b][b]&#91;J&#93;[/b]但是在今天的美国——一个不平等加剧、种族隔离日益严重、中产阶级工资停滞不前的国家——圣何塞地区真的能再次成为一个机会之地吗？[/trans][/p][p] [b]&#91;K&#93;[/b] The idea that those at the bottom can rise to the top is central to America’s ideas about itself.   [/b][b]&#91;H&#93;[/b]（36）[u]一些圣何塞居民说，随着近年来不平等的加剧，向上流动变得更加困难。[/u]随着硅谷成为更多成功企业的发源地，大量人口涌入该地区，导致房价飙升。从大多数标准来看，圣何塞已不再是低收入甚至中等收入家庭能够负担得起生活的地方。2006年至2014年期间，圣何塞的房租上涨了42.6%，是该国同期租金涨幅最大的。这座城市无家可归的问题日益严重，人们在2014年试图通过关闭美国最大的无家可归者临时居住地之一“丛林”来解决这个问题。不平等现象极为严重。人类发展指数——衡量预期寿命、受教育程度和人均收入的指标——为东圣何塞打出4.85分（满分为10分），而附近的苹果总部所在地库比蒂诺得分为9.26分。圣何塞过去曾经拥有许多令人愉快的因素——廉价的住房、靠近快速发展的工业、紧密联系的移民社区——这些共同为即使是最贫困的居民带来了繁荣的可能性。（44）[u]但近年来，房价飞涨，该地区贫富分化，中产阶级工作岗位消失。鉴于此，该地区穷人的未来看起来不像以前那么光明了。[/u][/p][p][b]      [/b][b]&#91;I&#93;（[/b]41）[u]圣何塞的领导人决心确保该市重新获得它的地位，再次成为一个即使是贫穷的孩子也可以获取成功资源的地方。[/u]硅谷就在它的后院，它当然有机会做到这一点。圣何塞市长萨姆·利卡多说：“我认为，硅谷有一个广泛的意识，我们可以做得更好，而不是让成千上万的邻居在一个非凡的成功时期被抛在身后。”[/p][p][b]      [/b][b]&#91;J&#93;[/b]但是在今天的美国——一个不平等加剧、种族隔离日益严重、中产阶级工资停滞不前的国家——圣何塞地区真的能再次成为一个机会之地吗？[/p][p][b]      [/b][b]&#91;K&#93;[/b]（38）[u]认为底层的人可以上升到上层的想法是美国自我观念的核心。这种流动性在圣何塞变得越来越困难，引发了人们对该基本信念的持久性质疑。毕竟，如果无法修复这片曾经的机会之地，那对美国其他地区来说又意味着什么呢？[/u][/p]\",\"words\":null,\"transWords\":null,\"title\":\"2020年12月 Jose’s officials are resolved to give poor kids access to the resources necessary for success in life. [/p]\",\"material\":{\"id\":272640,\"content\":\"[p=align:center][b]The Place Where the Poor Once Thrived[/b][trans][b]一个穷人曾经欣欣向荣的地方[/b][/trans][/p][p] [b]&#91;A&#93;[/b] This is the land of opportunity. If that weren’t already implied by the landscape—rolling green hills, palm trees, sun-kissed flowers—then it’s evident in the many stories of people who [phrase=171239]grew up[/phrase] poor in these sleepy neighborhoods and rose to enormous success. People like Tri Tran, who fled Vietnam on a boat in 1986, showed up in San Jose with nothing, made it to MIT, and then founded the food-delivery start-up Munchery, which is valued at $300 million. [trans][b]      &#91; A&#93;[/b]这是一片充满机遇的十地，即这里的风景——连绵起伏的青山、棕榈树、阳光亲吻的花朵——没有暗示出这样的机遇，那么从许多在这些寂静的社区里成长，并获得了巨大成功的穷人的故事中就可以明显地看出这一点。特里·特兰等人于1986年乘船逃离越南，到达圣何塞时一无所有，然后成功地进入麻省理工学院，之后创立了送餐初创公司Munchery（吃不厌的外卖订餐网站），目前估值3亿美元。[/trans][/p][p] [b]&#91;B&#93;[/b] Indeed, data suggests that this is one of the best places to [phrase=171239]grow up[/phrase] poor in America. A child born in the early 1980s into a low-income family in San Jose had a 12.9 percent chance of becoming a high earner as an adult, [phrase=158128]according to[/phrase] a landmark study released in 2014 by the economist Raj Chetty and his colleagues from Harvard and Berkeley. That number—12.9 percent—may not seem remarkable, but it was: Kids in San Jose whose families fell in the bottom [i]quintile[/i] (五分位数) of income nationally had the best shot in the country at reaching the top quintile. [trans][b]      [/b][b]&#91;B&#93;[/b]（39）[u]事实上，数据显示这是美国最适合穷人成长的地方之一。2014年，哈佛大学及伯克利分校的经济学家拉吉·切蒂及其同事发布了一项具有里程碑意义的研究。根据这项研究，20世纪80年代初出生于圣何塞低收入家庭的孩子成年后成为高收入者的概率为12.9%，这一数字——12.9%——似乎并不令人瞩目，但它确实令人瞩目：圣何塞那些收入在全国最低的五分之一的家庭的孩子，最有可能成为全国收入最高的五分之一。[/u][/trans][/p][p] [b]&#91;C&#93;[/b] [phrase=197882]By contrast[/phrase], just 4.4 percent of poor kids in Charlotte [phrase=177699]moved up[/phrase] to the top; in Detroit the figure was 5.5 percent. San Jose had social mobility comparable to Denmark’s and Canada’s and higher than other progressive cities [phrase=201452]such as[/phrase] Boston and Minneapolis.[trans][b]      [/b][b]&#91;C&#93;[/b]相比之下，夏洛特市只有4.4%的贫困儿童升入顶端；底特律的这一比例为5.5%。（43）[u]圣何塞的社会流动性可与丹麦和加拿大相提并论，高于波士顿和明尼阿波利斯等其他进步城市。[/u][/trans][/p][p] [b]&#91;D&#93;[/b] The reasons kids in San Jose performed so well might seem obvious. Some of the world’s most innovative companies are located here, providing opportunities [phrase=201452]such as[/phrase] the one seized by a 12-year-old Mountain View resident named Steve Jobs when he called William Hewlett to ask for spare parts and subsequently received a summer job. This is a city of immigrants—38 percent of the city’s population today is foreign-born—and immigrants and their children have historically experienced significant upward mobility in America. The city has long had a large foreign-born population (26.5 percent in 1990), leading to broader diversity, which, the Harvard and Berkeley economists say, is a good predictor of mobility. [trans][b]      [/b][b]&#91;D&#93;[/b]圣何塞的孩子表现如此出色的原因似乎是显而易见的。一些世界上最具创新精神的公司都坐落在这里，提供了这样的机会，比如：12岁的山景城居民史蒂夫·乔布斯就抓住了这样的机会。当时，他给威廉·休利特打电话申请备用件，随后获得了一份暑期工作。（37）[u]这是一个移民城市——如今该市38%的人口是在外国出生的——在美国历史上，移民及其子女经历了社会中显著的向上流动。[/u]长期以来，这座城市拥有大量的外国出生人口（1990年为26.5%），这导致了更广泛的多样性，哈佛大学和伯克利分校的经济学家说，这是一个很好的预测流动性的指标。[/trans][/p][p] [b]&#91;E&#93;[/b] Indeed, the streets of San Jose seem, [phrase=201349]in some ways[/phrase], to embody the best of America. It’s possible to drive in [phrase=201487]a matter of[/phrase] minutes from [i]sleek[/i] (光亮的) office towers near the airport where people pitch ideas to investors, to single-family homes with orange trees in their yards, or to a Vietnamese mall. The libraries here offer programs in 17 languages, and there are areas [phrase=201213]filled with[/phrase] small businesses owned by Vietnamese immigrants, Mexican immigrants, Korean immigrants, and Filipino immigrants, to name [phrase=201394]a few[/phrase]. [trans][b]      [/b][b]&#91;E&#93;[/b]（42）[u]的确，在某些方面，圣何塞的街道似乎体现了美国最好的一面。[/u]人们可以在机场附近时尚光亮的写字楼里向投资者推销创意，也可以在几分钟内驱车前往院子里种着橘子树的独户住宅，或者到一个越南购物中心。这里的图书馆提供17种语言的项目，并且这里到处都是由越南移民、墨西哥移民、韩国移民、菲律宾移民（举几个例子）经营的小企业。[/trans][/p][p] [b]&#91;F&#93;[/b] But researchers aren’t sure exactly why poor kids in San Jose did so well. The city has a low prevalence of children [phrase=171239]growing up[/phrase] in single-parent families, and a low level of concentrated poverty, both factors that usually mean a city [phrase=158691]allows for[/phrase] good intergenerational mobility. But San Jose also performs poorly on some of the measures [phrase=201477]correlated with[/phrase] good mobility. It is one of the most unequal places out of the 741 that the researchers measured, and it has high degrees of racial and economic [i]segregation[/i] (隔离). Its schools underperform based on how much money there is in the area, said Ben Scuderi, a predoctoral fellow at the Equality of Opportunity Project at Harvard, which uses big data to study how to improve economic opportunities for low-income children. “There’s [phrase=112277]a lot[/phrase] [phrase=170649]going on[/phrase] here which we don’t totally understand,” he said. “It’s interesting, because it [phrase=174474]kind of[/phrase] defies our expectations.”[trans][b]      [/b][b]&#91;F&#93;[/b]（43）[u]但研究人员并不能完全确定为什么圣何塞的穷孩子做得这么好。[/u]这座城市的单亲家庭儿童比例较低，集中贫困程度较低，这两个因素通常意味着一个城市能够实现良好的代际流动。但圣何塞在一些与良好流动性相关的指标方面也表现不佳。在研究人员测量的741个地方中，它是最不平等的地方之一，它有着高度的种族和经济隔离。哈佛大学机会均等项目利用大数据研究如何改善低收入儿童的经济机会。该项目博士预科研究员本·斯库德利表示，根据该地区的资金状况，这里的学校表现不佳。他说：“这里有很多我们不能完全理解的事情。这很有趣，因为这有点儿出乎我们的意料。”[/trans][/p][p] [b]&#91;G&#93;[/b] The Chetty data shows that neighborhoods and places mattered for children born in the San Jose area of the 1980s. Whether the city still [phrase=158691]allows for[/phrase] upward mobility of poor kids today, though, is up for debate. Some of the indicators [phrase=201452]such as[/phrase] income inequality, measured by the Equality of Opportunity Project for the year 2000, have only worsened in the past 16 years.[trans][b]      [/b][b]&#91;G&#93;[/b]切蒂的数据显示，对于20世纪80年代出生在圣何塞地区的孩子来说，社区和地方至关重要。（40）[u]不过，如今这座城市是否还允许贫困儿童向上流动，还有待商榷。[/u]一些指标，如2000年机会平等项目衡量的收入不平等，在过去16年里恶化了。[/trans][/p][p] [b]&#91;H&#93;[/b] Some San Jose residents say that as inequality has grown in recent years, upward mobility has become much more difficult to achieve. As Silicon Valley has become home to more successful companies, the flood of people to the area has caused housing prices to skyrocket. By most measures, San Jose is [phrase=178433]no longer[/phrase] a place where low-income, or even middle-income families, can [phrase=196421]afford to[/phrase] live. Rents in San Jose grew 42.6 percent between 2006 and 2014, which was the largest increase in the country during that time period. The city has a growing homelessness problem, which it tried to address by [phrase=185688]shutting down[/phrase] “The Jungle,” one of the largest homeless [i]encampments[/i] (临时住地) in the nation, in 2014. Inequality is extreme. The Human Development Index—a measure of life expectancy, education and [i]per capita[/i] (人均的) income—gives East San Jose a score of 4.85 out of 10, while nearby Cupertino, where Apple’s headquarters sits, receives a 9.26, San Jose [phrase=148491]used to[/phrase] have a happy mix of factors—cheap housing, closeness to a rapidly developing industry, tightly-knit immigrant communities—that together [phrase=179401]opened up[/phrase] the possibility of prosperity for even its poorest residents. But in recent years, housing prices have skyrocketed, the region’s rich and poor have segregated, and middle-class jobs have disappeared. Given this, the future for the region’s poor doesn’t look nearly as bright as it once did.   [/b][b]&#91;D&#93;[/b]圣何塞的孩子表现如此出色的原因似乎是显而易见的。一些世界上最具创新精神的公司都坐落在这里，提供了这样的机会，比如：12岁的山景城居民史蒂夫·乔布斯就抓住了这样的机会。当时，他给威廉·休利特打电话申请备用件，随后获得了一份暑期工作。（37）[u]这是一个移民城市——如今该市38%的人口是在外国出生的——在美国历史上，移民及其子女经历了社会中显著的向上流动。[/u]长期以来，这座城市拥有大量的外国出生人口（1990年为26.5%），这导致了更广泛的多样性，哈佛大学和伯克利分校的经济学家说，这是一个很好的预测流动性的指标。[/p][p][b]      [/b][b]&#91;E&#93;[/b]（42）[u]的确，在某些方面，圣何塞的街道似乎体现了美国最好的一面。[/u]人们可以在机场附近时尚光亮的写字楼里向投资者推销创意，也可以在几分钟内驱车前往院子里种着橘子树的独户住宅，或者到一个越南购物中心。这里的图书馆提供17种语言的项目，并且这里到处都是由越南移民、墨西哥移民、韩国移民、菲律宾移民（举几个例子）经营的小企业。[/p][p][b]      [/b][b]&#91;F&#93;[/b]（43）[u]但研究人员并不能完全确定为什么圣何塞的穷孩子做得这么好。[/u]这座城市的单亲家庭儿童比例较低，集中贫困程度较低，这两个因素通常意味着一个城市能够实现良好的代际流动。但圣何塞在一些与良好流动性相关的指标方面也表现不佳。在研究人员测量的741个地方中，它是最不平等的地方之一，它有着高度的种族和经济隔离。哈佛大学机会均等项目利用大数据研究如何改善低收入儿童的经济机会。该项目博士预科研究员本·斯库德利表示，根据该地区的资金状况，这里的学校表现不佳。他说：“这里有很多我们不能完全理解的事情。这很有趣，因为这有点儿出乎我们的意料。”[/p][p][b]      [/b][b]&#91;G&#93;[/b]切蒂的数据显示，对于20世纪80年代出生在圣何塞地区的孩子来说，社区和地方至关重要。（40）[u]不过，如今这座城市是否还允许贫困儿童向上流动，还有待商榷。[/u]一些指标，如2000年机会平等项目衡量的收入不平等，在过去16年里恶化了。[/p][p][b]      [/b][b]&#91;H&#93;[/b]（36）[u]一些圣何塞居民说，随着近年来不平等的加剧，向上流动变得更加困难。[/u]随着硅谷成为更多成功企业的发源地，大量人口涌入该地区，导致房价飙升。从大多数标准来看，圣何塞已不再是低收入甚至中等收入家庭能够负担得起生活的地方。2006年至2014年期间，圣何塞的房租上涨了42.6%，是该国同期租金涨幅最大的。这座城市无家可归的问题日益严重，人们在2014年试图通过关闭美国最大的无家可归者临时居住地之一“丛林”来解决这个问题。不平等现象极为严重。人类发展指数——衡量预期寿命、受教育程度和人均收入的指标——为东圣何塞打出4.85分（满分为10分），而附近的苹果总部所在地库比蒂诺得分为9.26分。圣何塞过去曾经拥有许多令人愉快的因素——廉价的住房、靠近快速发展的工业、紧密联系的移民社区——这些共同为即使是最贫困的居民带来了繁荣的可能性。（44）[u]但近年来，房价飞涨，该地区贫富分化，中产阶级工作岗位消失。鉴于此，该地区穷人的未来看起来不像以前那么光明了。[/u][/p][p][b]      [/b][b]&#91;I&#93;（[/b]41）[u]圣何塞的领导人决心确保该市重新获得它的地位，再次成为一个即使是贫穷的孩子也可以获取成功资源的地方。[/u]硅谷就在它的后院，它当然有机会做到这一点。圣何塞市长萨姆·利卡多说：“我认为，硅谷有一个广泛的意识，我们可以做得更好，而不是让成千上万的邻居在一个非凡的成功时期被抛在身后。”[/p][p][b]      [/b][b]&#91;J&#93;[/b]但是在今天的美国——一个不平等加剧、种族隔离日益严重、中产阶级工资停滞不前的国家——圣何塞地区真的能再次成为一个机会之地吗？[/p][p][b]      [/b][b]&#91;K&#93;[/b]（38）[u]认为底层的人可以上升到上层的想法是美国自我观念的核心。这种流动性在圣何塞变得越来越困难，引发了人们对该基本信念的持久性质疑。毕竟，如果无法修复这片曾经的机会之地，那对美国其他地区来说又意味着什么呢？[/u][/p]\",\"words\":null,\"transWords\":null,\"title\":\"2020年12月 Thrived[/b][trans][b]一个穷人曾经欣欣向荣的地方[/b][/trans][/p][p] [b]&#91;A&#93;[/b] This is the land of opportunity. If that weren’t already implied by the landscape—rolling green hills, palm trees, sun-kissed flowers—then it’s evident in the many stories of people who [phrase=171239]grew up[/phrase] poor in these sleepy neighborhoods and rose to enormous success. People like Tri Tran, who fled Vietnam on a boat in 1986, showed up in San Jose with nothing, made it to MIT, and then founded the food-delivery start-up Munchery, which is valued at $300 million. [trans][b]      &#91; A&#93;[/b]这是一片充满机遇的十地，即这里的风景——连绵起伏的青山、棕榈树、阳光亲吻的花朵——没有暗示出这样的机遇，那么从许多在这些寂静的社区里成长，并获得了巨大成功的穷人的故事中就可以明显地看出这一点。特里·特兰等人于1986年乘船逃离越南，到达圣何塞时一无所有，然后成功地进入麻省理工学院，之后创立了送餐初创公司Munchery（吃不厌的外卖订餐网站），目前估值3亿美元。[/trans][/p][p] [b]&#91;B&#93;[/b] Indeed, data suggests that this is one of the best places to [phrase=171239]grow up[/phrase] poor in America. A child born in the early 1980s into a low-income family in San Jose had a 12.9 percent chance of becoming a high earner as an adult, [phrase=158128]according to[/phrase] a landmark study released in 2014 by the economist Raj Chetty and his colleagues from Harvard and Berkeley. That number—12.9 percent—may not seem remarkable, but it was: Kids in San Jose whose families fell in the bottom [i]quintile[/i] (五分位数) of income nationally had the best shot in the country at reaching the top quintile. [trans][b]      [/b][b]&#91;B&#93;[/b]（39）[u]事实上，数据显示这是美国最适合穷人成长的地方之一。2014年，哈佛大学及伯克利分校的经济学家拉吉·切蒂及其同事发布了一项具有里程碑意义的研究。根据这项研究，20世纪80年代初出生于圣何塞低收入家庭的孩子成年后成为高收入者的概率为12.9%，这一数字——12.9%——似乎并不令人瞩目，但它确实令人瞩目：圣何塞那些收入在全国最低的五分之一的家庭的孩子，最有可能成为全国收入最高的五分之一。[/u][/trans][/p][p] [b]&#91;C&#93;[/b] [phrase=197882]By contrast[/phrase], just 4.4 percent of poor kids in Charlotte [phrase=177699]moved up[/phrase] to the top; in Detroit the figure was 5.5 percent. San Jose had social mobility comparable to Denmark’s and Canada’s and higher than other progressive cities [phrase=201452]such as[/phrase] Boston and Minneapolis.[trans][b]      [/b][b]&#91;C&#93;[/b]相比之下，夏洛特市只有4.4%的贫困儿童升入顶端；底特律的这一比例为5.5%。（43）[u]圣何塞的社会流动性可与丹麦和加拿大相提并论，高于波士顿和明尼阿波利斯等其他进步城市。[/u][/trans][/p][p] [b]&#91;D&#93;[/b] The reasons kids in San Jose performed so well might seem obvious. Some of the world’s most innovative companies are located here, providing opportunities [phrase=201452]such as[/phrase] the one seized by a 12-year-old Mountain View resident named Steve Jobs when he called William Hewlett to ask for spare parts and subsequently received a summer job. This is a city of immigrants—38 percent of the city’s population today is foreign-born—and immigrants and their children have historically experienced significant upward mobility in America. The city has long had a large foreign-born population (26.5 percent in 1990), leading to broader diversity, which, the Harvard and Berkeley economists say, is a good predictor of mobility. [trans][b]      [/b][b]&#91;D&#93;[/b]圣何塞的孩子表现如此出色的原因似乎是显而易见的。一些世界上最具创新精神的公司都坐落在这里，提供了这样的机会，比如：12岁的山景城居民史蒂夫·乔布斯就抓住了这样的机会。当时，他给威廉·休利特打电话申请备用件，随后获得了一份暑期工作。（37）[u]这是一个移民城市——如今该市38%的人口是在外国出生的——在美国历史上，移民及其子女经历了社会中显著的向上流动。[/u]长期以来，这座城市拥有大量的外国出生人口（1990年为26.5%），这导致了更广泛的多样性，哈佛大学和伯克利分校的经济学家说，这是一个很好的预测流动性的指标。[/trans][/p][p] [b]&#91;E&#93;[/b] Indeed, the streets of San Jose seem, [phrase=201349]in some ways[/phrase], to embody the best of America. It’s possible to drive in [phrase=201487]a matter of[/phrase] minutes from [i]sleek[/i] (光亮的) office towers near the airport where people pitch ideas to investors, to single-family homes with orange trees in their yards, or to a Vietnamese mall. The libraries here offer programs in 17 languages, and there are areas [phrase=201213]filled with[/phrase] small businesses owned by Vietnamese immigrants, Mexican immigrants, Korean immigrants, and Filipino immigrants, to name [phrase=201394]a few[/phrase]. [trans][b]      [/b][b]&#91;E&#93;[/b]（42）[u]的确，在某些方面，圣何塞的街道似乎体现了美国最好的一面。[/u]人们可以在机场附近时尚光亮的写字楼里向投资者推销创意，也可以在几分钟内驱车前往院子里种着橘子树的独户住宅，或者到一个越南购物中心。这里的图书馆提供17种语言的项目，并且这里到处都是由越南移民、墨西哥移民、韩国移民、菲律宾移民（举几个例子）经营的小企业。[/trans][/p][p] [b]&#91;F&#93;[/b] But researchers aren’t sure exactly why poor kids in San Jose did so well. The city has a low prevalence of children [phrase=171239]growing up[/phrase] in single-parent families, and a low level of concentrated poverty, both factors that usually mean a city [phrase=158691]allows for[/phrase] good intergenerational mobility. But San Jose also performs poorly on some of the measures [phrase=201477]correlated with[/phrase] good mobility. It is one of the most unequal places out of the 741 that the researchers measured, and it has high degrees of racial and economic [i]segregation[/i] (隔离). Its schools underperform based on how much money there is in the area, said Ben Scuderi, a predoctoral fellow at the Equality of Opportunity Project at Harvard, which uses big data to study how to improve economic opportunities for low-income children. “There’s [phrase=112277]a lot[/phrase] [phrase=170649]going on[/phrase] here which we don’t totally understand,” he said. “It’s interesting, because it [phrase=174474]kind of[/phrase] defies our expectations.”[trans][b]      [/b][b]&#91;F&#93;[/b]（43）[u]但研究人员并不能完全确定为什么圣何塞的穷孩子做得这么好。[/u]这座城市的单亲家庭儿童比例较低，集中贫困程度较低，这两个因素通常意味着一个城市能够实现良好的代际流动。但圣何塞在一些与良好流动性相关的指标方面也表现不佳。在研究人员测量的741个地方中，它是最不平等的地方之一，它有着高度的种族和经济隔离。哈佛大学机会均等项目利用大数据研究如何改善低收入儿童的经济机会。该项目博士预科研究员本·斯库德利表示，根据该地区的资金状况，这里的学校表现不佳。他说：“这里有很多我们不能完全理解的事情。这很有趣，因为这有点儿出乎我们的意料。”[/trans][/p][p] [b]&#91;G&#93;[/b] The Chetty data shows that neighborhoods and places mattered for children born in the San Jose area of the 1980s. Whether the city still [phrase=158691]allows for[/phrase] upward mobility of poor kids today, though, is up for debate. Some of the indicators [phrase=201452]such as[/phrase] income inequality, measured by the Equality of Opportunity Project for the year 2000, have only worsened in the past 16 years.[trans][b]      [/b][b]&#91;G&#93;[/b]切蒂的数据显示，对于20世纪80年代出生在圣何塞地区的孩子来说，社区和地方至关重要。（40）[u]不过，如今这座城市是否还允许贫困儿童向上流动，还有待商榷。[/u]一些指标，如2000年机会平等项目衡量的收入不平等，在过去16年里恶化了。[/trans][/p][p] [b]&#91;H&#93;[/b] Some San Jose residents say that as inequality has grown in recent years, upward mobility has become much more difficult to achieve. As Silicon Valley has become home to more successful companies, the flood of people to the area has caused housing prices to skyrocket. By most measures, San Jose is [phrase=178433]no longer[/phrase] a place where low-income, or even middle-income families, can [phrase=196421]afford to[/phrase] live. Rents in San Jose grew 42.6 percent between 2006 and 2014, which was the largest increase in the country during that time period. The city has a growing homelessness problem, which it tried to address by [phrase=185688]shutting down[/phrase] “The Jungle,” one of the largest homeless [i]encampments[/i] (临时住地) in the nation, in 2014. Inequality is extreme. The Human Development Index—a measure of life expectancy, education and [i]per capita[/i] (人均的) income—gives East San Jose a score of 4.85 out of 10, while nearby Cupertino, where Apple’s headquarters sits, receives a 9.26, San Jose [phrase=148491]used to[/phrase] have a happy mix of factors—cheap housing, closeness to a rapidly developing industry, tightly-knit immigrant communities—that together [phrase=179401]opened up[/phrase] the possibility of prosperity for even its poorest residents. But in recent years, housing prices have skyrocketed, the region’s rich and poor have segregated, and middle-class jobs have disappeared. Given this, the future for the region’s poor doesn’t look nearly as bright as it once did. A&#93;[/b]这是一片充满机遇的十地，即这里的风景——连绵起伏的青山、棕榈树、阳光亲吻的花朵——没有暗示出这样的机遇，那么从许多在这些寂静的社区里成长，并获得了巨大成功的穷人的故事中就可以明显地看出这一点。特里·特兰等人于1986年乘船逃离越南，到达圣何塞时一无所有，然后成功地进入麻省理工学院，之后创立了送餐初创公司Munchery（吃不厌的外卖订餐网站），目前估值3亿美元。[/p][p][b]      [/b][b]&#91;B&#93;[/b]（39）[u]事实上，数据显示这是美国最适合穷人成长的地方之一。2014年，哈佛大学及伯克利分校的经济学家拉吉·切蒂及其同事发布了一项具有里程碑意义的研究。根据这项研究，20世纪80年代初出生于圣何塞低收入家庭的孩子成年后成为高收入者的概率为12.9%，这一数字——12.9%——似乎并不令人瞩目，但它确实令人瞩目：圣何塞那些收入在全国最低的五分之一的家庭的孩子，最有可能成为全国收入最高的五分之一。[/u][/p][p][b]      [/b][b]&#91;C&#93;[/b]相比之下，夏洛特市只有4.4%的贫困儿童升入顶端；底特律的这一比例为5.5%。（43）[u]圣何塞的社会流动性可与丹麦和加拿大相提并论，高于波士顿和明尼阿波利斯等其他进步城市。[/u][/p][p][b]      [/b][b]&#91;D&#93;[/b]圣何塞的孩子表现如此出色的原因似乎是显而易见的。一些世界上最具创新精神的公司都坐落在这里，提供了这样的机会，比如：12岁的山景城居民史蒂夫·乔布斯就抓住了这样的机会。当时，他给威廉·休利特打电话申请备用件，随后获得了一份暑期工作。（37）[u]这是一个移民城市——如今该市38%的人口是在外国出生的——在美国历史上，移民及其子女经历了社会中显著的向上流动。[/u]长期以来，这座城市拥有大量的外国出生人口（1990年为26.5%），这导致了更广泛的多样性，哈佛大学和伯克利分校的经济学家说，这是一个很好的预测流动性的指标。[/p][p][b]      [/b][b]&#91;E&#93;[/b]（42）[u]的确，在某些方面，圣何塞的街道似乎体现了美国最好的一面。[/u]人们可以在机场附近时尚光亮的写字楼里向投资者推销创意，也可以在几分钟内驱车前往院子里种着橘子树的独户住宅，或者到一个越南购物中心。这里的图书馆提供17种语言的项目，并且这里到处都是由越南移民、墨西哥移民、韩国移民、菲律宾移民（举几个例子）经营的小企业。[/p][p][b]      [/b][b]&#91;F&#93;[/b]（43）[u]但研究人员并不能完全确定为什么圣何塞的穷孩子做得这么好。[/u]这座城市的单亲家庭儿童比例较低，集中贫困程度较低，这两个因素通常意味着一个城市能够实现良好的代际流动。但圣何塞在一些与良好流动性相关的指标方面也表现不佳。在研究人员测量的741个地方中，它是最不平等的地方之一，它有着高度的种族和经济隔离。哈佛大学机会均等项目利用大数据研究如何改善低收入儿童的经济机会。该项目博士预科研究员本·斯库德利表示，根据该地区的资金状况，这里的学校表现不佳。他说：“这里有很多我们不能完全理解的事情。这很有趣，因为这有点儿出乎我们的意料。”[/p][p][b]      [/b][b]&#91;G&#93;[/b]切蒂的数据显示，对于20世纪80年代出生在圣何塞地区的孩子来说，社区和地方至关重要。（40）[u]不过，如今这座城市是否还允许贫困儿童向上流动，还有待商榷。[/u]一些指标，如2000年机会平等项目衡量的收入不平等，在过去16年里恶化了。[/p][p][b]      [/b][b]&#91;H&#93;[/b]（36）[u]一些圣何塞居民说，随着近年来不平等的加剧，向上流动变得更加困难。[/u]随着硅谷成为更多成功企业的发源地，大量人口涌入该地区，导致房价飙升。从大多数标准来看，圣何塞已不再是低收入甚至中等收入家庭能够负担得起生活的地方。2006年至2014年期间，圣何塞的房租上涨了42.6%，是该国同期租金涨幅最大的。这座城市无家可归的问题日益严重，人们在2014年试图通过关闭美国最大的无家可归者临时居住地之一“丛林”来解决这个问题。不平等现象极为严重。人类发展指数——衡量预期寿命、受教育程度和人均收入的指标——为东圣何塞打出4.85分（满分为10分），而附近的苹果总部所在地库比蒂诺得分为9.26分。圣何塞过去曾经拥有许多令人愉快的因素——廉价的住房、靠近快速发展的工业、紧密联系的移民社区——这些共同为即使是最贫困的居民带来了繁荣的可能性。（44）[u]但近年来，房价飞涨，该地区贫富分化，中产阶级工作岗位消失。鉴于此，该地区穷人的未来看起来不像以前那么光明了。[/u][/p][p][b]      [/b][b]&#91;I&#93;（[/b]41）[u]圣何塞的领导人决心确保该市重新获得它的地位，再次成为一个即使是贫穷的孩子也可以获取成功资源的地方。[/u]硅谷就在它的后院，它当然有机会做到这一点。圣何塞市长萨姆·利卡多说：“我认为，硅谷有一个广泛的意识，我们可以做得更好，而不是让成千上万的邻居在一个非凡的成功时期被抛在身后。”[/p][p][b]      [/b][b]&#91;J&#93;[/b]但是在今天的美国——一个不平等加剧、种族隔离日益严重、中产阶级工资停滞不前的国家——圣何塞地区真的能再次成为一个机会之地吗？[/p][p][b] Thrived[/b][trans][b]一个穷人曾经欣欣向荣的地方[/b][/trans][/p][p] [b]&#91;A&#93;[/b] This is the land of opportunity. If that weren’t already implied by the landscape—rolling green hills, palm trees, sun-kissed flowers—then it’s evident in the many stories of people who [phrase=171239]grew up[/phrase] poor in these sleepy neighborhoods and rose to enormous success. People like Tri Tran, who fled Vietnam on a boat in 1986, showed up in San Jose with nothing, made it to MIT, and then founded the food-delivery start-up Munchery, which is valued at $300 million. [trans][b]      &#91; A&#93;[/b]这是一片充满机遇的十地，即这里的风景——连绵起伏的青山、棕榈树、阳光亲吻的花朵——没有暗示出这样的机遇，那么从许多在这些寂静的社区里成长，并获得了巨大成功的穷人的故事中就可以明显地看出这一点。特里·特兰等人于1986年乘船逃离越南，到达圣何塞时一无所有，然后成功地进入麻省理工学院，之后创立了送餐初创公司Munchery（吃不厌的外卖订餐网站），目前估值3亿美元。[/trans][/p][p] [b]&#91;B&#93;[/b] Indeed, data suggests that this is one of the best places to [phrase=171239]grow up[/phrase] poor in America. A child born in the early 1980s into a low-income family in San Jose had a 12.9 percent chance of becoming a high earner as an adult, [phrase=158128]according to[/phrase] a landmark study released in 2014 by the economist Raj Chetty and his colleagues from Harvard and Berkeley. That number—12.9 percent—may not seem remarkable, but it was: Kids in San Jose whose families fell in the bottom [i]quintile[/i] (五分位数) of income nationally had the best shot in the country at reaching the top quintile. [trans][b]      [/b][b]&#91;B&#93;[/b]（39）[u]事实上，数据显示这是美国最适合穷人成长的地方之一。2014年，哈佛大学及伯克利分校的经济学家拉吉·切蒂及其同事发布了一项具有里程碑意义的研究。根据这项研究，20世纪80年代初出生于圣何塞低收入家庭的孩子成年后成为高收入者的概率为12.9%，这一数字——12.9%——似乎并不令人瞩目，但它确实令人瞩目：圣何塞那些收入在全国最低的五分之一的家庭的孩子，最有可能成为全国收入最高的五分之一。[/u][/trans][/p][p] [b]&#91;C&#93;[/b] [phrase=197882]By contrast[/phrase], just 4.4 percent of poor kids in Charlotte [phrase=177699]moved up[/phrase] to the top; in Detroit the figure was 5.5 percent. San Jose had social mobility comparable to Denmark’s and Canada’s and higher than other progressive cities [phrase=201452]such as[/phrase] Boston and Minneapolis.[trans][b]      [/b][b]&#91;C&#93;[/b]相比之下，夏洛特市只有4.4%的贫困儿童升入顶端；底特律的这一比例为5.5%。（43）[u]圣何塞的社会流动性可与丹麦和加拿大相提并论，高于波士顿和明尼阿波利斯等其他进步城市。[/u][/trans][/p][p] [b]&#91;D&#93;[/b] The reasons kids in San Jose performed so well might seem obvious. Some of the world’s most innovative companies are located here, providing opportunities [phrase=201452]such as[/phrase] the one seized by a 12-year-old Mountain View resident named Steve Jobs when he called William Hewlett to ask for spare parts and subsequently received a summer job. This is a city of immigrants—38 percent of the city’s population today is foreign-born—and immigrants and their children have historically experienced significant upward mobility in America. The city has long had a large foreign-born population (26.5 percent in 1990), leading to broader diversity, which, the Harvard and Berkeley economists say, is a good predictor of mobility. [trans][b]      [/b][b]&#91;D&#93;[/b]圣何塞的孩子表现如此出色的原因似乎是显而易见的。一些世界上最具创新精神的公司都坐落在这里，提供了这样的机会，比如：12岁的山景城居民史蒂夫·乔布斯就抓住了这样的机会。当时，他给威廉·休利特打电话申请备用件，随后获得了一份暑期工作。（37）[u]这是一个移民城市——如今该市38%的人口是在外国出生的——在美国历史上，移民及其子女经历了社会中显著的向上流动。[/u]长期以来，这座城市拥有大量的外国出生人口（1990年为26.5%），这导致了更广泛的多样性，哈佛大学和伯克利分校的经济学家说，这是一个很好的预测流动性的指标。[/trans][/p][p] [b]&#91;E&#93;[/b] Indeed, the streets of San Jose seem, [phrase=201349]in some ways[/phrase], to embody the best of America. It’s possible to drive in [phrase=201487]a matter of[/phrase] minutes from [i]sleek[/i] (光亮的) office towers near the airport where people pitch ideas to investors, to single-family homes with orange trees in their yards, or to a Vietnamese mall. The libraries here offer programs in 17 languages, and there are areas [phrase=201213]filled with[/phrase] small businesses owned by Vietnamese immigrants, Mexican immigrants, Korean immigrants, and Filipino immigrants, to name [phrase=201394]a few[/phrase]. [trans][b]      [/b][b]&#91;E&#93;[/b]（42）[u]的确，在某些方面，圣何塞的街道似乎体现了美国最好的一面。[/u]人们可以在机场附近时尚光亮的写字楼里向投资者推销创意，也可以在几分钟内驱车前往院子里种着橘子树的独户住宅，或者到一个越南购物中心。这里的图书馆提供17种语言的项目，并且这里到处都是由越南移民、墨西哥移民、韩国移民、菲律宾移民（举几个例子）经营的小企业。[/trans][/p][p] [b]&#91;F&#93;[/b] But researchers aren’t sure exactly why poor kids in San Jose did so well. The city has a low prevalence of children [phrase=171239]growing up[/phrase] in single-parent families, and a low level of concentrated poverty, both factors that usually mean a city [phrase=158691]allows for[/phrase] good intergenerational mobility. But San Jose also performs poorly on some of the measures [phrase=201477]correlated with[/phrase] good mobility. It is one of the most unequal places out of the 741 that the researchers measured, and it has high degrees of racial and economic [i]segregation[/i] (隔离). Its schools underperform based on how much money there is in the area, said Ben Scuderi, a predoctoral fellow at the Equality of Opportunity Project at Harvard, which uses big data to study how to improve economic opportunities for low-income children. “There’s [phrase=112277]a lot[/phrase] [phrase=170649]going on[/phrase] here which we don’t totally understand,” he said. “It’s interesting, because it [phrase=174474]kind of[/phrase] defies our expectations.”[trans][b]      [/b][b]&#91;F&#93;[/b]（43）[u]但研究人员并不能完全确定为什么圣何塞的穷孩子做得这么好。[/u]这座城市的单亲家庭儿童比例较低，集中贫困程度较低，这两个因素通常意味着一个城市能够实现良好的代际流动。但圣何塞在一些与良好流动性相关的指标方面也表现不佳。在研究人员测量的741个地方中，它是最不平等的地方之一，它有着高度的种族和经济隔离。哈佛大学机会均等项目利用大数据研究如何改善低收入儿童的经济机会。该项目博士预科研究员本·斯库德利表示，根据该地区的资金状况，这里的学校表现不佳。他说：“这里有很多我们不能完全理解的事情。这很有趣，因为这有点儿出乎我们的意料。”[/trans][/p][p] [b]&#91;G&#93;[/b] The Chetty data shows that neighborhoods and places mattered for children born in the San Jose area of the 1980s. Whether the city still [phrase=158691]allows for[/phrase] upward mobility of poor kids today, though, is up for debate. Some of the indicators [phrase=201452]such as[/phrase] income inequality, measured by the Equality of Opportunity Project for the year 2000, have only worsened in the past 16 years.[trans][b]      [/b][b]&#91;G&#93;[/b]切蒂的数据显示，对于20世纪80年代出生在圣何塞地区的孩子来说，社区和地方至关重要。（40）[u]不过，如今这座城市是否还允许贫困儿童向上流动，还有待商榷。[/u]一些指标，如2000年机会平等项目衡量的收入不平等，在过去16年里恶化了。[/trans][/p][p] [b]&#91;H&#93;[/b] Some San Jose residents say that as inequality has grown in recent years, upward mobility has become much more difficult to achieve. As Silicon Valley has become home to more successful companies, the flood of people to the area has caused housing prices to skyrocket. By most measures, San Jose is [phrase=178433]no longer[/phrase] a place where low-income, or even middle-income families, can [phrase=196421]afford to[/phrase] live. Rents in San Jose grew 42.6 percent between 2006 and 2014, which was the largest increase in the country during that time period. The city has a growing homelessness problem, which it tried to address by [phrase=185688]shutting down[/phrase] “The Jungle,” one of the largest homeless [i]encampments[/i] (临时住地) in the nation, in 2014. Inequality is extreme. The Human Development Index—a measure of life expectancy, education and [i]per capita[/i] (人均的) income—gives East San Jose a score of 4.85 out of 10, while nearby Cupertino, where Apple’s headquarters sits, receives a 9.26, San Jose [phrase=148491]used to[/phrase] have a happy mix of factors—cheap housing, closeness to a rapidly developing industry, tightly-knit immigrant communities—that together [phrase=179401]opened up[/phrase] the possibility of prosperity for even its poorest residents. But in recent years, housing prices have skyrocketed, the region’s rich and poor have segregated, and middle-class jobs have disappeared. Given this, the future for the region’s poor doesn’t look nearly as bright as it once did.     [/b][b]&#91;F&#93;[/b]（43）[u]但研究人员并不能完全确定为什么圣何塞的穷孩子做得这么好。[/u]这座城市的单亲家庭儿童比例较低，集中贫困程度较低，这两个因素通常意味着一个城市能够实现良好的代际流动。但圣何塞在一些与良好流动性相关的指标方面也表现不佳。在研究人员测量的741个地方中，它是最不平等的地方之一，它有着高度的种族和经济隔离。哈佛大学机会均等项目利用大数据研究如何改善低收入儿童的经济机会。该项目博士预科研究员本·斯库德利表示，根据该地区的资金状况，这里的学校表现不佳。他说：“这里有很多我们不能完全理解的事情。这很有趣，因为这有点儿出乎我们的意料。”[/p][p][b]      [/b][b]&#91;G&#93;[/b]切蒂的数据显示，对于20世纪80年代出生在圣何塞地区的孩子来说，社区和地方至关重要。（40）[u]不过，如今这座城市是否还允许贫困儿童向上流动，还有待商榷。[/u]一些指标，如2000年机会平等项目衡量的收入不平等，在过去16年里恶化了。[/p][p][b] If that weren’t already implied by the landscape—rolling green hills, palm trees, sun-kissed flowers—then it’s evident in the many stories of people who [phrase=171239]grew up[/phrase] poor in these sleepy neighborhoods and rose to enormous success. People like Tri Tran, who fled Vietnam on a boat in 1986, showed up in San Jose with nothing, made it to MIT, and then founded the food-delivery start-up Munchery, which is valued at $300 million. [trans][b]      &#91; A&#93;[/b]这是一片充满机遇的十地，即这里的风景——连绵起伏的青山、棕榈树、阳光亲吻的花朵——没有暗示出这样的机遇，那么从许多在这些寂静的社区里成长，并获得了巨大成功的穷人的故事中就可以明显地看出这一点。特里·特兰等人于1986年乘船逃离越南，到达圣何塞时一无所有，然后成功地进入麻省理工学院，之后创立了送餐初创公司Munchery（吃不厌的外卖订餐网站），目前估值3亿美元。[/trans][/p][p] [b]&#91;B&#93;[/b] Indeed, data suggests that this is one of the best places to [phrase=171239]grow up[/phrase] poor in America. That number—12.9 percent—may not seem remarkable, but it was: Kids in San Jose whose families fell in the bottom [i]quintile[/i] (五分位数) of income nationally had the best shot in the country at reaching the top quintile. [trans][b]      [/b][b]&#91;B&#93;[/b]（39）[u]事实上，数据显示这是美国最适合穷人成长的地方之一。2014年，哈佛大学及伯克利分校的经济学家拉吉·切蒂及其同事发布了一项具有里程碑意义的研究。根据这项研究，20世纪80年代初出生于圣何塞低收入家庭的孩子成年后成为高收入者的概率为12.9%，这一数字——12.9%——似乎并不令人瞩目，但它确实令人瞩目：圣何塞那些收入在全国最低的五分之一的家庭的孩子，最有可能成为全国收入最高的五分之一。[/u][/trans][/p][p] [b]&#91;C&#93;[/b] [phrase=197882]By contrast[/phrase], just 4.4 percent of poor kids in Charlotte [phrase=177699]moved up[/phrase] to the top; in Detroit the figure was 5.5 percent. San Jose had social mobility comparable to Denmark’s and Canada’s and higher than other progressive cities [phrase=201452]such as[/phrase] Boston and Minneapolis.[trans][b]      [/b][b]&#91;C&#93;[/b]相比之下，夏洛特市只有4.4%的贫困儿童升入顶端；底特律的这一比例为5.5%。（43）[u]圣何塞的社会流动性可与丹麦和加拿大相提并论，高于波士顿和明尼阿波利斯等其他进步城市。[/u][/trans][/p][p] [b]&#91;D&#93;[/b] The reasons kids in San Jose performed so well might seem obvious. Some of the world’s most innovative companies are located here, providing opportunities [phrase=201452]such as[/phrase] the one seized by a 12-year-old Mountain View resident named Steve Jobs when he called William Hewlett to ask for spare parts and subsequently received a summer job. This is a city of immigrants—38 percent of the city’s population today is foreign-born—and immigrants and their children have historically experienced significant upward mobility in America. The city has long had a large foreign-born population (26.5 percent in 1990), leading to broader diversity, which, the Harvard and Berkeley economists say, is a good predictor of mobility. It’s possible to drive in [phrase=201487]a matter of[/phrase] minutes from [i]sleek[/i] (光亮的) office towers near the airport where people pitch ideas to investors, to single-family homes with orange trees in their yards, or to a Vietnamese mall. The libraries here offer programs in 17 languages, and there are areas [phrase=201213]filled with[/phrase] small businesses owned by Vietnamese immigrants, Mexican immigrants, Korean immigrants, and Filipino immigrants, to name [phrase=201394]a few[/phrase]. [trans][b]      [/b][b]&#91;E&#93;[/b]（42）[u]的确，在某些方面，圣何塞的街道似乎体现了美国最好的一面。[/u]人们可以在机场附近时尚光亮的写字楼里向投资者推销创意，也可以在几分钟内驱车前往院子里种着橘子树的独户住宅，或者到一个越南购物中心。这里的图书馆提供17种语言的项目，并且这里到处都是由越南移民、墨西哥移民、韩国移民、菲律宾移民（举几个例子）经营的小企业。[/trans][/p][p] [b]&#91;F&#93;[/b] But researchers aren’t sure exactly why poor kids in San Jose did so well.
